## Migration Analysis

Your code has three patterns that won't work on .NET 8 (`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`):

| Pattern Found | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `ProcessLoop` while loop | `CancellationToken` |
| **ThreadAbortException catch** | catch block with rollback | `OperationCanceledException` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | keeps thread alive after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic that was in the ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control the loop condition.
                // Loop will exit naturally because token.IsCancellationRequested is true.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish
        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
            {
                // Thread didn't stop in time — log a warning.
                // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in .NET 8.
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes to `GetNextItem`

The blocking `GetNextItem()` **must** be updated to accept and respect the token — otherwise cancellation stalls until it unblocks on its own:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could break out
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks forever
}

// AFTER — wakes up promptly on cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}
```

If you're using a `BlockingCollection<T>`, it already accepts a `CancellationToken`. If it's a custom blocking call, replace the wait with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(timeout)` or an async alternative.

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing the token to `GetNextItem`** | The whole point of `Thread.Abort` was to break out of a blocking call. Without the token, `Stop()` hangs until the call returns on its own. |
| **Forgetting `IDisposable`** | `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` in other paths** | Replace any `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so it's cancellable. |
| **Uncooperative thread won't stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, there is **no forcible kill** in .NET 8. If the thread truly can't cooperate, you must move the work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one. |
